  "prompt": "Is magnesium considered a solid, liquid or gas and why?",
  "response": "Magnesium is considered a solid at room temperature and standard pressure. This classification is based on its melting point and boiling point. Magnesium has a melting point of about 650 degrees Celsius (1202 degrees Fahrenheit) and a boiling point of about 1090 degrees Celsius (1994 degrees Fahrenheit). Since room temperature is typically around 20-25 degrees Celsius (68-77 degrees Fahrenheit), magnesium remains in its solid state under normal conditions.\n\nThe reason magnesium is a solid at room temperature is due to its atomic structure and the strong metallic bonds between its atoms. These bonds require a significant amount of energy to break, which is why magnesium needs to be heated to a high temperature before it transitions from a solid to a liquid, and then to a gas.",
